Excercise 4: Mixed membership models

Consider a subset of the data of end-of-year addresses of the presidents of the Italian Republic (in the course Team files) from 1992 (beginning of Scalfaro office) to 2021 (end of Mattarella first office). Select nouns, adjectives and verbs with a frequency of at least 5 occurrences as textual units of analysis. Fit a topic model by opportunely choosing the model structure – whether and how incorporating metadata (President and speech year) for detecting any significant influence on topic structure, and number of topics. Comment on the results and provide an effective visualization to help understanding.

Data loading, cleaning and preprocessing

Data loading

Loading the data and displaying an overview: from 1992 (beginning of Scalfaro) to 2021 (end of Mattarella):

pathtofile <- "datasets/Corpus EndofYear/Corpus EoY lemm/"

pres_dat <- readtext(paste0(pathtofile, "*.txt"), encoding = "UTF-8")

# Filter to include only the last 30 speeches: from SCALFARO_1992 to MATTARELLA_2021
pres_dat <- pres_dat %>% tail(30)

# Extracting metadata: year and president
pres_dat <- pres_dat %>%
  mutate(
    year = as.integer(str_extract(doc_id, "\\d{4}")),  # Extracts four consecutive digits as the year
    pres = str_extract(doc_id, "[A-Z]+")  # Extracts consecutive uppercase letters as the president's name
    )

# Display an overview
print(pres_dat, n = 30)

There is some preprocessing that needs to be done before fitting the topic model. We will keep nouns (_N and _NM), adjectives (_A) and verbs (_V) with a frequency of at least 5 occurrences as textual units of analysis.

Data cleaning

Fisrt, let’s remove extra characters and POS tags:

# filtering on POS tags:
pres_dat$text <- pres_dat$text %>%
    gsub("\n", " ", .) %>%
    noquote %>%
    str_replace_all(., "[,;.:()?!°'%«»-]", " ") %>% # Remove punctuation
    # filtering out POS tags:
    # with a blank space before the POS tag
    gsub(" \\w+_CONG", "", .) %>%
    gsub(" \\w+_DET", "", .) %>%
    gsub(" \\w+_PREP", "", .) %>%
    gsub(" \\w+_AVV", "", .) %>%
    gsub(" \\w+_NUM", "", .) %>%
    gsub(" \\w+_PRON", "", .) %>%
    gsub(" \\w+_ESC", "", .) %>%
    gsub(" \\w+_O ", " ", .) %>%
    # without a blank space before the POS tag
    gsub("\\w+_CONG", "", .) %>%
    gsub("\\w+_DET", "", .) %>%
    gsub("\\w+_PREP", "", .) %>%
    gsub(" \\w+_AVV", "", .) %>%
    gsub(" \\w+_NUM", "", .) %>%
    gsub("\\w+_PRON", "", .) %>%
    gsub(" \\w+_ESC", "", .) %>%
    gsub("\\w+_O ", " ", .)


# removing POS tags:
pres_dat$text <- pres_dat$text %>%
    gsub("_NM", "", .) %>%
    gsub("_N", "", .) %>%
    gsub("_A", "", .) %>%
    gsub("_V", "", .)

It’s evident that the most frequent words are “essere” and “avere”, however, we can avoid considering them in the analysis, since they would not provide any meaningful information.

Model fitting

Ideal number of topics

Before fitting the models, we need to decide how many topics to consider in the analysis. For this task, we will use searchK and FindTopicsNumber.

  • searchK: we’ll do 2 runs without metadata and 2 runs with metadata (president and year) to see if the inclusion of metadata affects the number of topics ideal for the models.
k_search <- 2:50  # Tests from 2 to 50 topics

#without metadata:
#k1
start_time <- Sys.time() # Start timing
kResult_1 <- searchK(out$documents,
                     out$vocab,
                     K = k_search,
                     verbose = F,
                     heldout.seed = 2138)
end_time <- Sys.time()
k_1_time = end_time - start_time
cat("The 1st k search took:", k_1_time, "seconds\n")
save(kResult_1, file = "k_r1.Rdata")

#k2
start_time <- Sys.time() # Start timing
kResult_2 <- searchK(out$documents,
                     out$vocab,
                     K = k_search,
                     verbose = F,
                     heldout.seed = 83120)
end_time <- Sys.time()

cat("The 2nd k search took:", k_2_time, "seconds\n")
save(kResult_2, file = "k_r2.Rdata")


# with metadata:

  • with FindTopicsNumber:
result <- FindTopicsNumber(
    dati_dfm,
    topics = seq(from = 2, to = 50, by = 1),
    metrics = c("Griffiths2004", "CaoJuan2009", "Arun2010", "Deveaud2014"),
    method = "Gibbs",
    control = list(seed = 02138),
    mc.cores = 3L,  # Adjust based on your system capability
    verbose = TRUE
)
save(result, file = "k_ldatuning.Rdata")

It looks like, overall, 8 might be a good number of topics to consider.

Without covariates

As a first model, we’ll fit a STM without covariates and with 8 topics:

  • with spectral initialization:
Fit0_spectral <- stm(out$documents, 
            out$vocab, 
            K = 8, 
            data = out$meta, 
            init.type = "Spectral", 
            max.em.its = 500,
            seed = 2138, 
            verbose = F)

save(Fit0_spectral, file = "stm_0.RData")
  • with the selectModel function:
Fit0_select <- selectModel(out$documents, out$vocab, K = 8, data = out$meta, max.em.its = 500, verbose = TRUE,
    init.type = "LDA", runs = 20, seed = 2138)

save(Fit0_select, file = "stm_0_select.RData")

The Exclusivity is similar, but the Semantic Coherence is higher for the selected model. Hence, we’ll choose the selected model as the best one without covariates.

With covariates

For the model fitting with covariates we’ll try two different approaches:

  • putting pres and year as prevalence covariates;

  • putting year as a prevalence covariate and pres as content covariate. #### pres and year as Prevalence Covariate For this one, let’s try to fit one model with 8 topics and another one with 36 topics:

Fit_prevalence <- stm(out$documents, 
                      out$vocab, 
                      K = 8, 
                      prevalence = ~ year + pres, 
                      data = out$meta, 
                      init.type = "Spectral", 
                      max.em.its = 500, 
                      seed = 2138, 
                      verbose = FALSE)

Fit_prevalence_36 <- stm(out$documents, 
                      out$vocab, 
                      K = 36, 
                      prevalence = ~ year + pres, 
                      data = out$meta, 
                      init.type = "Spectral", 
                      max.em.its = 500, 
                      seed = 2138, 
                      verbose = FALSE)

## 8 topics model:
## Exclusivity: 7.917404
## Semantic Coherence: -3.338722
## 
## 
## 36 topics model:
## Exclusivity: 9.004029
## Semantic Coherence: -8.088916

Even though the Exclusivity is a little higher for the 36 topics model, the Semantic Coherence is too low compared to the 8 topics model. Hence, we’ll use 8 as number of topics.

pres as a Content Covariate

Fit_content <- stm(documents = out$documents, 
                   vocab = out$vocab, 
                   K = 8, 
                   prevalence = ~ year, 
                   content = ~ pres, 
                   data = out$meta, 
                   init.type = "Spectral", 
                   max.em.its = 500, 
                   seed = 2138, 
                   verbose = FALSE)

Model evaluation and Results

Topic shares within the documents

  • Fit0_selectedmodel:

  • Fit_prevalence:

  • Fit_content:

Most topics have document-topic proportions concentrated near 0. This indicates that each document is typically associated with only a few dominant topics, which is a sign of well-fitted topic models for many real-world corpora.

Furthermore, the presence of low document-topic proportions for most topics suggests the topics are distinct and not overlapping too much. This means that the model successfully identifies different thematic clusters.

Topic correlation

  • Fit0_selectedmodel:

  • Fit_prevalence:

  • Fit_content:

Apart from topic 7 and 1 in the Fit0_selectedmodel, there seems to be no correlation between the topics.

A higher grade of correlation between topics could indicate that the STM model is not well-suited for this data. In that case, a CTM could be more appropriate.

Not only year is significant (red line) for each topic, but it also gives historical context to the topics. For example, by looking at the trend around the year 2020 and its top words, it looks like topic 3 might refer to the COVID-19 pandemic.

Top words with labelTopics function

Another way to explore the words associated with each topic, is using the labelTopics function. This function provides: - Words with the highest probability of appearing in each topic. - FREX words, which balance frequency and exclusivity. - Lift and Score metrics, which prioritize words that are less common across other topics.

These last three metrics are particularly useful for identifying the most representative words for each topic. Relying solely on highest probability words may be less informative, as many frequently used terms tend to appear repeatedly across the texts, as seen in the plot of common words used by presidents.

Perspectives plot

The last thing we can do is examine the perspective plots. These plots illustrate how various words are linked to specific topics for two presidents. The size of the words represents their significance within the topic, while their color and placement reflect their connection to each president.

For example, we can compare the perspectives of SCALFARO and CIAMPI for the content model in the 3rd topic:

plot(Fit_content, type = "perspectives", topics = 3, covarlevels = c("SCALFARO" ,"CIAMPI"))

This plot reveals how Italy’s adoption of the Euro on January 1, 2002, may be reflected in the topic distribution for CIAMPI (the word ‘europeo’) but is not prominently highlighted for SCALFARO.
